All these tests use `StringUtils.equals`. The bug is triggered when the two CharSequences are not both Strings and have different lengths. In the tests, they use StringBuilder and String. For example, `StringUtils.equals("abc", new StringBuilder("abcd"))` would trigger the bug because one is String, one is StringBuilder, so it goes to the `regionMatches` branch, and lengths differ (3 vs 4). Using `Math.max` would cause `regionMatches` to compare up to index 3 of the shorter sequence (length 3), but `regionMatches` expects both sequences to have at least that many characters? Actually, `regionMatches` signature: `regionMatches(CharSequence, boolean, int, CharSequence, int, int)`. It will compare up to `len` characters starting from offsets. If we pass `Math.max(cs1.length(), cs2.length())` as the length, and one is shorter, the method might try to read past the end of the shorter sequence, causing IndexOutOfBoundsException or returning false incorrectly. The bug is that it uses `Math.max` instead of `Math.min`. So tests that compare sequences of different lengths (non-String) will fail.

